@Azaria S , 

Check out the opening paragraph mentioning that 2250 people participated in this survey. That will help answer your wondering about how many people each dot represents, and you can even get a good approximation of the number of people in the survey who chose gymnastics.

But don't stop thinking about just the number 2250. Who are those 2250 people and how did they get included in this survey? Do you think these 2250 are representative of your community, or are they even representative of all NYT Magazine readers? If your community would be asked the same question, do you think you'd get similar results from the survey as we did from this survey of NYT subscribers?

@Addy, I love that thought. 
So let's think about this - how do you think the data would have changed if instead of oil painting they had asked about just painting, or painting and drawing? And instead of neuroscience, they had said medicine, and instead of gymnastics, they had said athletics? And instead of "three languages of your choice" they had said "Japanese, Arabic, and Russian"? 
So I wonder, like you, what made the author of this poll create the choices given in this chart.

@Yomi , 

I like your headline! I think it really captures in few words what this question is all about.

Do you think that they chose wisely in offering gymnastics as the one sport in this list of six options? What might you have done differently? What might you add to the set of choices and what might you delete?

@Alex Perez , 

What can you find in the text that tells you something about the population? Do you think those participants are representative of all Americans, of all people from Minnesota, or are they representative of some other group?

How do you think the results would differ if this same survey were given to all students in your school?

@Emma , 
I like that you wonder why they chose to display the data in this way, using colored circles instead of a dot plot or bar graph. If you took these same data and made a bar graph, how do you think it would change the conclusions you'd make?
Also, how do you think the people in your community in Minnesota would respond differently than the people in this survey?

@Emma , 
I like that you wondered why they chose to use colored circles to represent the data instead of a dot plot or bar graph. If you made a bar graph from these data, how do you think it would affect any conclusions you might make about the data collected?

Also, how do you think your community in Minnesota differs from the 2250 people who responded to this survey?
